\begin_layout Section
Autoregressive (AR) model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Autoregressive model is one type of time series model that uses for describing
 the time-varying process.
 The model is flexible in handling various kinds of time series patterns.
 The name autoregressive comes from how the model performs a regression
 of the variable against its own previous outputs 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cryer1986time"

\end_inset

.
 The number of autoregressive lags is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, an autoregressive model of order 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 or AR(p) model can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t}=c+\phi_{1}y_{t-1}+\phi_{2}y_{t-2}+...+\phi_{p}y_{t-p}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{t}=c+\sum_{i=1}^{p}\phi_{i}y_{t-i}+\varepsilon_{t}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is a constant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 are coefficients in the autoregression and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is Gaussian white noise with zero mean and variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is equal to one, the model is called the first order autoregression process
 or AR(1).
\end_layout

